        <p>This is a visualization of the typical way we understand racial disparities in policing; we typically count the number of stops by race, adjust for population demographics of the area in question and then compare how likely people of different races are to be stopped. In this case, I tallied up the number of stops by race and then divided those numbers by the numbers of people of each race recorded as living in Rhode Island in the 2010 Census.</p>
        <p>This methodology gives rise to the often touted statistic that black drivers are <code>2.5</code> times more likely to be stopped than their white counterparts in Rhode Island.</p>
